# How I Evaluate Crypto Projects: My Personal Checklist

When I first started getting into crypto, I didn't have any system. I'd just read a whitepaper, look at a fancy website, and think, "Cool, this might blow up." Spoiler: most of the time it didn't. And sometimes it just disappeared with the money.

Then I started keeping a spreadsheet. First just in a notebook, then in Excel, and now it's a whole framework that takes up pages and pages. I use it every single time I look at a new project. And you know what? Scam projects get filtered out by the third bullet point, and the solid ones stand out immediately.

Here it is. No fluff, just what actually works.

---

## 1. The People 🧑‍💻

This is the most important thing. You can buy technology, you can copy code, but you can't buy a team. If the project is run by sketchy people hiding behind cat avatars, I don't even look further.

**What I do:**

- **Go to LinkedIn.** I look for everyone listed on the site. If someone doesn't have a LinkedIn — already weird. If they do, but it was created yesterday with one post — also weird. If the profile is alive, has history, real recommendations from actual colleagues — that's a plus.

- **Check what they did before.** Have they had a successful project? Or are they jumping from one ICO to another? There are people in crypto who just run around collecting money for new ideas while abandoning the old ones. You can spot them pretty quickly.

- **Look at the developers' GitHub.** What did they commit before this? Any open-source projects? Or is their GitHub empty while the website claims they're "top developers"?

- **Message them.** Yeah, I just reach out on LinkedIn or in Telegram groups. Ask some simple question. If they reply quickly, professionally, and politely — good sign. If they ignore or get rude — well, you get it.

**My red flags:**

- Anonymous team. No faces at all.
- Profile photos are stock images. Easy to check: save the photo and Google it.
- No experience in the field they're working in. Building DeFi but spent their whole life selling asphalt.
- On LinkedIn they have like 50 connections, all equally anonymous.

**Real story:** There was this project with "team photos" on their site. I saved the CEO's picture, Googled it — turned out to be a stock photo. Asked them on Telegram why they're using fake images. Got banned. Project rugged a month later.

