## 4. Security 🔒

Simple: if the code is leaky, nothing else matters.

**What I check:**

- **Was there an audit?** Mandatory. If no audit — I don't even look further. Period.

- **Who did the audit?** CertiK, Hacken, Cyberscope, Fairyproof — those are top tier. If it's some random firm I've never heard of — I read the report very carefully. Often shady firms will write "all good" for money.

- **Link to the report.** Not a screenshot on the website, but an actual PDF where you can see all the details.

- **What does the report say?** If it says "no critical vulnerabilities" — good. If it says "a few medium issues, we'll fix later" — worse.

- **Is the contract verified?** Go to Etherscan or BscScan, paste the contract address. If there's a green "Verified" badge — code is open, you can look. If not — stop.

- **Suspicious functions.** Check for `mint` (can print unlimited tokens), `blacklist` (can block wallets), `pause` (can stop trading), `renounceOwnership` (did they give up control). If present — questions.

- **Bug bounty.** If they have a bug bounty program, they take security seriously.

**My rules:**

- No audit — no go.
- Audit from a sketchy firm — read it myself, often it's...
- Contract not verified — also no go.

