## 7. My Personal Rules 🧠

Over the years, I've developed a few rules that save me money and nerves.

**1. I don't fall in love with a project.** Emotions are the enemy of analysis. If I really like an idea, I actively look for flaws. And I almost always find them.

**2. I don't average down.** If a project is falling — I was wrong about the entry. Throwing more money into a sinking project is a sure way to lose everything. Better to cut losses and move on.

**3. I check the team personally.** Not just LinkedIn — I message them. Ask something uncomfortable. Watch their reaction.

**4. I compare with competitors.** If the project isn't better than three similar ones — why do I need it?

**5. I read the whitepaper.** Yes, it's boring. But that's where the traps are. Often in fine print, things they don't mention in the ads.

**6. Trust, but verify.** Audit is mandatory, but I still use my own eyes.

---

## 8. 5-Minute Quick Check

If I'm short on time, I run through this fast list:

- [ ] Team not anonymous? (quick LinkedIn check)
- [ ] Audit exists? (top firm, link works)
- [ ] Tokenomics not obviously scammy? (team under 20%, has lock-up)
- [ ] Product is real? (testnet, MVP)
- [ ] Community isn't bots? (comments, questions)
- [ ] Partnerships are real? (checked partner sites)
- [ ] Marketing without "100x" promises?

If at least three answers are "no" — the project goes in the trash. No second look.

